TWILIGHT SORT HAD A LEAKER CALLED IN BY A INBOUND SUPERVISOR WHO DISCOVEREND A LEAKING HAZMAT INSIDE OF A TRAILER. THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE PSC TO TELL A DESIGNATED RESPONDER OF THE PACKAGE. THE SINGLE PACKAGE WAS BEARING AN CORROSIVE DIAMOND LABEL ON IT AND LIQUID WAS SEEN COMING OUT OF THE CORNERS OF THE PACKAGE. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED TO THAT LOCATION AS SOON AS POSSIBLE WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART AND WEARING FULL PPE. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER THEN USED THE REVISED JANUARY 2022 DECISION TREE AND TURN TO THE CORROSIVE RESPONSER SHEET. THE DESIGNATED ERSPONDER READ THE ENTIRE RESPONSE SHEET AND REIEWED THE HAZARDS, PPE REQUIRED, RESPONSE ACTION STEPS, AND DECONTAMINATION SECTIONS. HAD AN INITAL PH READING OF 4 AND THEN USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NUETRALIZE THE SUBSTANCE. ONCE NUETRAL THEN THE RESPONSER SOLIDIFED THE SUBSTANCE WITH ZEP ZORBENT (MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN UP). THE PACKAGE AND MATERIALS WERE CONTAINERIZED ONCE THE AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED ALL BROUGHT BACK TO THE PSC.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: On September 2, 2022, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3082 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the concrete dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to perform the necessary corrective actions. FCE utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the impacted surface, then containerized all UN3082-impacted solids into one (1) 35-gallon drum. The damaged drum was placed into one (1) 85-gallon overpack for disposal.

LEAKING PACKAGE SPILL INSIDE OF A FEEDER. THE PSC WAS NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY AND DISPATCHED A TRAINED DESIGNATED RESPONDER TO THE SPILL LOCATION WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER WORE FULL PPE FOR UTILIZATION WHILE CLEANUP HAPPENED. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER USED THE REVISED JANUARY 2021 DECISION AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET TO BEGAN THE CLEAN UP. LIQUID WAS SEEN COMING FROM THE PACKAGE AND WAS TESTED IN AREA, PH 6. FOLLOWING THE DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURE THE RESPONDER USED MATERIALS TO SOLIDIFY THE LEAKING PACKAGE. On September 7, 2022, one (1) 5-gallon jerrican of Alpet D2 Surface Sanitizer (contains isopropanol) was punctured during a load shift and released approximately one-half (0.5) gallon of product to the dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from Parc Environmental to perform the necessary corrective actions. Parc personnel noted that the released product had evaporated upon their arrival, and dispersed the contents of the damaged jerrican into a new five (5)-gallon jerrican for disposal.

On September 7, 2022, at 1730 ET, Logiflex reported 10-gallons of  UN2735 "Accelerator 960-1 CH" released impacting the inside of the trailer and gravel from (40) 5-gallon plastic jugs due to falling over and having loose caps. ERTS dispatched Haz-Mat Response Inc. (HMRI) to the site to perform all onsite clean up operations. On September 7, 2022, at 2320 ET, HMRI arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of product released impacting the inside of the trailer and on product containers 6-feet (ft.) by 6ft., the outside of the trailer 4-ft. by 50-ft. and the gravel area beneath the passenger side of the rear axel 2-ft. by 2-ft. HMRI cleaned inside and outside of the trailer with a pressure washer, degreaser, and citric acid collected with a collapsible vinyl container. HMRI collected the impacted gravel with hand shovels, less than one inch in depth. HMRI collected and containerized solid waste liquids solidified with granular absorbents into (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was transported offsite for disposal.

column168: On 09/7/22, at 1636 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard, noted a strong vinegar odor in the yard near UTLX647315, a loaded tank car of Acetic Acid, Glacial, which was possibly leaking. The car was isolated and Celanese LTD, NRC, and IDEM were notified.  CHEMTREC#2022-0907-00387. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the Liquid Line blind flange nuts securing the valve to the pressure plate less then tool tight and the entire valve could be moved by hand. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Travis Robertson 713-816-7085. Contractor personnel secured the Liquid Line, remediated impacted ballast and tank car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport, pending OTMA-1 approval. This incident did require a special switching move. 7.1 is required.  Cause Code: 242 NARRI: 5
column169: (NAR:242 5 What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Connection between liquid line and closure (blind) flange Why Failed: Closure (blind) flange bolts/nuts - less than tool tight)  Shipper was advised to review loading practices with personnel and conduct investigation into check list load and unloading procedure failure.

On September 8, 2022, at 1549 ET, Logiflex reported 5-gallons of UN2735 "Accelerator 960-1 CH" impacting the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot from (40) 5-gallon jugs due to falling over and having loose caps. ERTS dispatched Haz-Mat Response Inc. (HMRI) to the site to perform all clean up operations. On September 8, 2022, at 2021 ET, HMRI arrived onsite and offloaded the trailer. HMRI estimated approximately 5-gallons of product released impacting the trailer floor and asphalt below. HMRI stated that the trailer will be taken to a truck wash once the clean up was completed, applied granular absorbents to the impacted areas, collected and containerized the absorbents into a 30-gallon poly drum. All waste was transported offsite for disposal.

PSC WAS CALLED OF A LEAKING PACKAGE AT THE PD2 LOADING DOCK. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER ARRIVED AT THE SPILL WITH FULL PPE (GOGGLES, BOOTS, APRON AND GLOVES USING SILVER SHIELD INNER LINER, AND SLEEVES) AND A FULLY STOCKED SPILL CART. UPON ARRIVING TO THE PACKAGE SPILL IT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE METAL GRATING OF THE LOADING DOCK, THE PACKAGE WAS ON ITS SIDE AND APPEARED WET FROM INSIDE. THE DESIGNATED RESPONDER CLEANED UP THE PACKAGE USING THE REVISED 2021 DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE STEPS ON PAGE 6, LIMITED QUANTITY. PH TESTED THE LIQUID, PH 6. CHANGED RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS ON PAGE 7. USED THE ZEP ZORBENT TO SOLIDIFY THE SUBSTANCE AND SWEPT THE REMAINDER OF DEBRIS IN THE AREA THOROUGHLY. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A LINED SPIL TRAY WITH DEBRIS AND TRANSPORTED TO THE PSC CAGE TO BE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP. UTILIZING THE DMP PROCEDURES OF THE WASTE DISPOSAL FLOW CHART TO BEGIN PROCESSING.

DECONTAMINATION WAS FOLLOWED PER THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THE PACKAGE AND MATERIALS WERE CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED IN LINED SPILL TRAYS TO BE BROUGHT TO THE PSC. column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN MIAMI, FLORIDA, A BLACK SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET DESTINED FOR GUATEMALA HAD ORIENTATION ARROWS ON THE OUTER BLACK SHRINK WRAP, BUT THE ARROWS WERE IN AN INCORRECT SIDEWAY ORIENTATION. UNCOVERING THE BLACK SHRINK WRAP REVEALED 15 BOXES WITH GREEN CERTIFIED MAIL STICKERS THAT APPEARED TO BE COVERING MARKS OR LABELS ORIGINALLY IN A DIAMOND SHAPE. UNCOVERING THE GREEN STICKERS REVEALED GROUND LTD QTY MARKS ON ALL 15 BOXES. OPENED PACKAGES AND FOUND FLAMMABLE AEROSOL CANS OF ANDIS COOL CARE PLUS FOR CLIPPER BLADES (UN1950 AEROSOLS FLAMMABLE). INSPECTION OF ALL ADDITIONAL PACKAGES OF THE CARGO FOUND ADDITIONAL BOXES WITH COVERED UN3481 LITHIUM BATTERY MARKS. SOME BOXES HAD THE APPEARANCE OF MARKS/LABELS BEING CUT FROM THE OUTER AND INNER BOXES. ONE UNMARKED BOX CONTAINED SIX INNER BOXES WITH 20 PHONES IN EACH BOX, EQUALING 120 PHONES. SequenceEvent: During the sunrise sort, the package was brought over to the hazmat cage with signs of internal leakage. The package will be returned to the shipper unless told otherwise on disposition. The bottle leaked about 3/4 of the "SWAN 99% ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL". DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: The package was immediately placed upright into a salvage drum lined with a hazmat bag to collect any possible further leakage and further inspection.

SequenceEvent: The driver carried the Hazmat box to the recipients door. When he was approaching he heard some drips. He obtained a plastic container from his truck and loaded the upside down box, with the gallon containers upright, into the plastic container. He drove the container back to the warehouse not leaking. He handed to QA and let QA know what happened. DescribePack: The 1 gallon container had a loose cap and the foil seal was open. This caused the container to leak quickly when the driver looked under the box to see why he saw some drips. By now the bottom of the container had the isopropanol on it and the bottom of the fiberboard box got weak and broke open. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The driver turned the box upside down and reloaded the 4 gallon containers into the upside down box. He stood the gallon containers upright to stop the leak.

column43: Drexel Defol® 5 Defoliant/Desiccant with Fire Retardant
column168: At 1707 EST, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at the terminal. It was reported that approximately 30 gallons of UN2428 Drexel Defol® 5 Defoliant/Desiccant with Fire Retardant released in Trailer #313-2894 from a 275 gallon poly tote due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched E3 Environmental to conduct cleanup. At 2215 ET, E3 personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 125 gallons of product released to a 60' x 20' area of the asphalt lot and trailer floor. Oil dri was deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The remaining product in the damaged tote was transferred out into (3) 55 gallon poly drums. All spent absorbents were then collected and containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized into 2 additional 55 gallon drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
NOT SECURED

column168: At the intermediate terminal in Harrisburg, it was discovered during the unloading process that the container was leaking. The investigation revealed that the drum had a small puncture hole caused by a protruding nail in a skid used for dunnage. The container was immediately placed into an overpack to prevent further release. The released material was neutralized and placed into a container for proper disposal. The identification markings were unable to be obtained safely.
column169: The incident may have been prevented had the dunnage skid been checked for protruding nails prior to being used. Using skids free from nails and protruding objects is a regular topic covered in dock safety meetings. This topic will continue to be covered to prevent further occurrences.

column168: At 1750 ET, XPO Logistics reported a spill that occurred inside a trailer at the XPO terminal in XDM in Des Moines, IA. The spill consisted of a 330 gallon metal tote of UN1992 Corr12525b, which was damaged prior to arrival at the terminal due to improper loading which caused the tote to be slightly punctured by loose debris inside the trailer, causing a gallon to release. ERTS dispatched EnviroServe to conduct cleanup. At 1120 ET, EnviroServe arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 gallons of product released to a 3' x 2' area of the trailer floor. The product left in the damaged tote was pumped out into a 275 gallon poly tote and one 40 gallon closed top poly drum. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted area and collected. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all cleanup debris into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 09/13/2022 at approximately 2051 hours personnel in the Hamlet yard reported a nineteen car derailment. In the derailment ETCX421006 a loaded tank car of Acetic Anhydride was found to be leaking from the base of the liquid line where it meets the pressure plate during the initial inspection by H/M James. The tank car was dripping about every 20 seconds. The car was isolated and the Shipper, Eastman Chemical Company was notified. Marion Environmental Inc (MEI) responded. The leak was contained until the tank car was set up during re-railing operations. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the Shipper Thomas McGourty 423-229-1491, TommMcGourt@Eastman.com. The tank car was isolated and will be transloaded by MEI.

column168: On the evening of 09/01/22 Flt NC730  a shipment of Dangerous Goods arrived in Bethel on a ULD.  After the cargo nets had been removed from the ULDs and the freight was being moved inside the warehouse an employee noticed a shipment had fallen off of the top of a stack of freight.   1. The employees’ were directed to not approach the shipment. 2. Time was given for any dangerous vapors to dissipate. 3. The shipment was restacked and moved to the farthest point on the property. 4. The possibly contaminated net and wrapping was moved to the same location. 5. The amount of the spill was determined to be approximately a cup or less of fluid. 6. The spill was diluted with water to keep it from being tracked into the building, and the containers were rinsed to keep anyone from accidentally touching the chemicals. 7. Consulted the ERG to make sure there were no further actions required.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING A STRONG PUNGENT ODOR BY THE LVD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-1. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THT OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 350 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: 1.  X-2022091287 A fiberboard box was found during the sort operation at the Memphis hub that was leaking. One side of that box was covered in what appeared to be paint. While investigating the package the spill agent discovered that the two 5L metal cans inside were heavily damaged. The lid on one of the cans came open releasing its contents. All the contents were placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended shippers declaration.   2. X-2022100242 During the PM sort operations at the FedEx Express hub in Memphis, TN a fiberboard box was observed leaking. Further investigation indicated the box contained a metal can of UN1263, Paint Related Material, PGII, which the inner contents leaked out from bottom into the outer packaging. Following the spill cleanup, the involved package was placed inside a salvage drum and held pending further disposition.  3. X-2022100243 During the PM sort operations at the FedEx Express hub in Memphis, TN a fiberboard box was observed leaking. Further investigation indicated the box contained two metal cans of un1263, Paint, PGII, which the inner contents leaked out into the outer packaging from the top of the can. Following the spill cleanup, the involved package was placed inside a salvage drum and held pending further disposition.

column168: On September 6, 2022, XPO Logistics Terminal LFY reported an approximate 1 gallon release of UN2924 EMBR11678A” from a 330 gallon poly tote. The top body of the poly tote was discovered punctured in the trailer upon arrival. One gallon released onto the trailer floor only. ERTS dispatched OMI for cleanup and containment operations.  On September 6, 2022 at 1030 EST, OMI personnel arrived onsite for cleanup operations. OMI confirmed approximately 1 gallon of product impacted a 5ft x 5ft area of trailer floor. The cause of release was a puncture to the top of the tote. LA State police officer Thomas Chance was onsite and arranged for the shipper to deliver a new tote for the remaining product. OMI transferred the remaining product into the new tote and cut up the old poly tote. The spilled product was cleaned with granular absorbents and pads, which were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum with the damaged tote body. All waste remained onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

WENT TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET ADDING SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE SUBSTANCE WAS NEUTRAL. ONCE NEUTRAL THE RESPONDER SOLIDIFIED THE MATERIAL USING ZEP, AND THEN DECONTAMINATED THE AREA. THE PACKAGE WITH THE MATERIALS WERE BROUGHT BACK IN TWO LINED SPILL TRAYS. THE WASTE DISPOSAL FOR A FULL DMP FLOW CHART WAS USED TO BEGIN THE PROCESS OF THE DAMAGED LEAKER. column168: RNLU100211 (Hazmat declared) was reported at the BNSF Stockton hub by a shipper pickup driver, as leaking an unknown liquid on the evening of 9/7/22. It was moved to the leaker pit & at the time was noted as non   active. A LARS inspection on 9/8/22 found an active leak of ~ 20 drops/min of a milky liquid, from midpoint towards the rear, with less than 2 gals released in the pit at time of inspection. The interior inspection found mixed LTL cargo with a pallet of 5 gal pails of Sani   Soft fallen over (Corrosive Class 8). column168: When the Brewster Yard Switch crew was switching out there train, the car inspector notice a strong odor from tank car CEWX 607.  He notified the yardmaster who had the train crew stop the train and segregate the locomotive from the cars.  The Yardmaster then notified myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  I came out to look at the car and removed protective housing cover seal #1464036 and found that the B end Liquid Valve was iced over.  I removed the ice and saw that the valve was leaking around the threads of the valve plug.  I tried to tighten the valve and was able to get a quarter turn out of it and then the leak stopped.  I then tried to tighten the valve plug and was able to get an additional 3/4 turn out of that.  I considered the car secure and released it for transportation.  I installed new seal #0000217 on the protective housing lid.
column169: Investigate this valve as to why it would work open.

column43: ALKYLDIMETHYL BENZYL AMMONIUM CHLORIDE, DIDECYLDIMETHYL AMMONIUM CHLORIDE,
column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND IN LESS THAN 1 MINUTE A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 12 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND SATURATE THE BASE OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ IN BURSTING TEST.

On September 02, 2022, Landstar contacted ERTS of a cargo release involving Clothianidin, UN3077 impacting the trailer floor.  ERTS dispatched a remediation contractor to address the reported UN3077 spill from supersack(s) on Trailer 696404. Following contractor arrival and assessment of the involved cargo, it was determined that the supersacks of concern were not damaged, but rather the tension strings on top of the supersacks were loose, which allowed the product to spill out. The contractor estimated that up to 4-cups of product spilled and affected trailer flooring components only. Product spilled was subsequently collected along with media applied to address affected trailer flooring components. Waste generated is currently pending disposal.

column42: PROPIONIC ACID WITH NOT LESS THAN 90% ACID BY MASS
column168: On 9/29/2022 at 0643, personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered ETCX 21077, a loaded tank car of Propionic Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, Kentucky EOC were notified. (CHEMTREC Report # 2022-0929-00058). Joe Taylor, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found two of eight manway securement bolts inadequately secured to affect a proper seal between the manway cover and nozzle resulting in a release of hazardous materials. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Tony Micks 314-413-7339. The manway was secured in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31, all released material was cleaned from the exterior of the car, and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 not required.   Cause Code:200 NARRI:100

column168: On September 8, 2022, at 0250 hours personnel in the CSXT ACCA yard at Richmond, Virginia, reported an odor in the area of CAOX 200164, a residue tank car last containing Chlorine.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Brenntag Mid-South, was notified via CHEMTREC Report #2022-0908-00082.  HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to investigate and found a vapor release from the tank car’s right side vapor line valve. Contractor personnel found product leaking through the valve while in the closed positon and the secondary closure plug not containing the release.  Contractor personnel tightened the secondary closure plug to stop the release.  A certified mobile repair unit (MRU) subsequently responded, removed and replaced the faulty valve, and performed a bubble leak test on the repair prior to the car being released for transpiration.

Contractor personnel found product leaking through the valve while in the closed positon and the secondary closure plug not containing the release.  Contractor personnel tightened the secondary closure plug to stop the release.  A certified mobile repair unit (MRU) subsequently responded, removed and replaced the faulty valve, and performed a bubble leak test on the repair prior to the car being released for transportation.

column168: On September 16, 2022, at 0514 ET, HOC Transport reported UN3295 "Natural Gasoline" unknown amount from a cargo tanker due to being involved in an accident and rolled over. ERTS dispatched HEPACO for all onsite clean up operations. On September 16, 2022, at 0705 ET, HEPACO arrived onsite and determined there were two punctures  approximately 1/2-inch in diameter and 2-inches by 3-inches in the tanker.  The New Pittsburgh Fire Department removed the driver from the truck and sprayed  fire fighting foam for suppression. Following the transfer of approximately 1,913-gallons of natural gasoline from the damaged tanker to a relief tanker, an estimated 6,887-gallons was released.  HEPACO reported one impacted storm drain that runs perpendicular to roadway-underneath the east bound lane to the south. The Fire Department installed absorbent boom for precautionary measure, no impacts to surface water. The truck and tanker were removed from the median.   HEPACO reported a 100-feet (ft.) by 6-ft. area of median soils and a 250-ft. by between 3 and 8-ft. width of shoulder ditch soils at drain outfall were impacted by the release. HEPACO reported a storm drain that was impacted located in the median and inspected the outfall, located to the south-east bound lane roadway, and found evidence of soil impacts. HEPACO utilized pads to absorb impacts at outfall followed by a high-pressure line jetter/vacuum truck unit from surface drain inside of catch basin and piping system to clean and recover approximately 200-gallons of liquids with vacuum truck. HEPACO utilized absorbent booms and pads in the impacted soil areas, storm drain and outfall to recover impacts, and replaced absorbents for preventative and containment measures pending monitoring and remedial activities (soil excavation). HEPACO collected and containerized all solid waste (absorbents) in a 55-gallon steel drum and transported offsite for disposal.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: 09/30/22 at 12:58 hours, it was reported to H/M Scoons that in Waterville Yard CPF 113 terminal personnel had discovered CTCX784021, a Loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gas, leaking from the protective housing area. The car was isolated and Williams OHIO Valley Midstream, were notified. (CHEMTREC 2022-09-30-00208. HEPACO a CSX contractor responded and found the tank car was leaking from the protective housing area. Upon claiming the railcar and accessing the protective housing it was fond that the liquid line valve was open, and the secondary securement plug was improperly installed. The issue was identified, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Chris Hanlon 304-312-9812 Chris.Hanlon@Williams.com. HEPACO personnel corrected the defects and secured the leak. Railcar car was released to transportation. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.
column169: Describe: (NAR code:119 5 What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve Where Failed: Closure plug Why Failed: Improperly installed , valve open)

column168: A Veolia employee was operating a rental forklift loading material on to a trailer. The forks of the lift were longer than usual and were protruding out on the other side of the pallet. When the employee went to place the pallet in the truck, the forks punctured a drum behind the pallet resulting in the release of about 20 gallons of material inside the trailer. No material leaked outside of the trailer.
column169: Following the incident on 9/26/2022, a discussion between the Veolia EHS manager and the Field Supervisor was conducted. The discussion addressed the importance of inspecting any forklift prior to use to ensure the user is familiar with the features of the forklift. There were also extensive discussions on regarding the awareness of the length of the forks on the lift prior to use to prevent drum punctures. In addition to this discussion, training will be held with the office addressing drum puncture prevention.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: A leaking cubic yard box was discovered as a trailer was moved to Veola's facility from the 10 day intransit yard in Menomonee Falls, WI. The package contained paint cans collected at a Household Hazardous Waste event.  One or more of the paint cans leaked and it is believed that at some point the liner was also punctured during the packing process.  The puncture allowed the leaking paint to seep out of the cubic yard box and onto the trailer floor.  The spill was approximately 1 gallon of paint which was cleaned up with oil dry and the cubic yard box was unpacked and repackaged.
column169: The employees that were part of packing the container were retrained on the process of properly packing paint cans into a cubic yard box. This included how to stack the cans, check for leaks and make sure the lids are secure.  Emphasis was placed on how to load caulk tubes in the CYB so it does not puncture the liner which is a possibility on how the liner was damaged.

column26: CORNER EASTERN MAIN ROAD  & TRINITY AVEN
column168: 1 of 3 boxes (Master TRK# 777924391336) was wet and all contents were lost.  The box contained 1 bottle and newspaper strips for dunnage.  The bottle was wrapped in a bubble wrap sheet and enclosed in a single clear plastic bag.  The bottom half of the bottle was shattered allowing the loss of all contents.  It is not reported how bottle came to shatter.  Per DG Admin, M. Drayden, packaging remnants are to be discarded/disposed.

column168: At 1748 ET, XPO terminal UPW contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred on the dock in Pasco, WA. The spill consisted of an unknown number of 1 gallon plastic jugs containing ZEP Big Z, which arrived already damaged in a carton containing four of the items, which was taken out of the trailer and was on the dock. ERTS dispatch GrayMar to conduct cleanup operations. At 1910 ET, contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 ounces of product released from a box containing (4) 1 gallon jugs. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected. The damaged box, jugs, and all cleanup debris was collected and containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum which was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Package was brought to the attention of the spill specialist at our Anchorage AK location when a red stain was found on the corner of the box indicating a spill. The source of the spill was bottle labeled as "Magenta," however, it could not be determined from where on the bottle the spill originated.  Package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for disposition.

column168: The shipper (Micronova) sent the goods to Expeditors facility in Chicago for consolidation with other shipments destined for the same destination and consignee on 9/7/2022.  The freight was not marked or labeled and there was no indication that the goods were DG based on any of the documentation provided by the shipper.  On 9/14/2022 the goods were consolidated with the other shipments received and readied for transport.  On 9/15/2022 the shipment was confirmed on board the flight under MAWB 172-56923252.  On 9/15/2022, Expeditors randomly pulled this file for a compliance review.  Expeditors compliance personnel asked operations to confirm with the shipper whether this shipment was DG or not due to the invoice description of some of the items.  On 9/16/2022 the shipper confirmed that the shipment was ID8000 Consumer Commodity moving under PI Y963.  Unfortunately at this point the freight was already at the final destination.
column169: The shipper has put in place the following corrective actions: - Shipper's entire shipping team will attend DG training via an external party to raise awareness. - Going forward all DG information will be flagged and provided to Expeditors at the time of booking. - Shipper has a continuous improvement mentality and will ensure that their DG process is reviewed for gaps.  Although Expeditors compliance personnel ultimately found the error, we have also reviewed our hidden DG policy with the operations personnel to bring heightened awareness to this issue.

column168: On 09/29/2022, at 1342 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg, WV Yard discovered INVX 26240 after being advised by an FRA Inspector, a loaded tank car of Hexamethylenediamine, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2022-0929-00244). Quick Respone, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a deteriorated manway nozzle gasket improperly secured resulted in the release of product at the manway nozzle. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Thomas Moon of INV Nylon Chemicals America, phone 316-252-7642. Contractor personnel properly installed a manway nozzle gasket and secured the manway cover per 49 CFR 173.31, and cleaned all spilled material from the exterior of the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.  Cause Code: 209 NARRI: 80
column169: (nar: 209 5 What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover Why Failed: Gasket deteriorated)

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On September 18, 2022, at approximately 15:07 hours, personnel in the CSX Brunswick, MD yard discovered SVCX 80505, a residue tank car of Hydrogen Chloride was leaking vapors from the top of the car.  The release was due to product leaking between the pressure relief device and the tank car’s pressure plate.  The car was isolated and the shipper, SI Group, was notified via CHEMTREC report 2022-0918-00025.  Specialized Professional Services, Inc., (SPSI), a CSX emergency response contractor, was dispatched to assist with the release.  Response personnel from SPSI and CSX’s Hazardous Materials Team installed a Midland Emergency Capping Kit to contain the product release. Response personnel then worked to safely purge the car of all residual vapor so the car could be move to home shop for repair as a clean/empty car.
column169: (NAR Code:409 5 What Failed: Reclosing Pressure Relief Device Where Failed: Connection between base of valve and manway cover plate Why Failed: Mounting flange gasket deteriorated)

column168: SUSPICIOUS PACKAGE ON ONE OF THE DRIVER'S VEHICLE. UPON ARRIVAL THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE BELIEVED A SHIPPER WAS IMPROPERLY SHIPPING HAZMATS. NOTICED WHITE BOXES WITH A GREEN DIAMOND LABEL GOING INTO UNMARKED BOXES THAT HE PICKED UP. RESPONDER MOVED THE BOXES TO THE HAZMAT AUDITING AREA AND OPENED THEM. THE BOXES CONTAINED TWO INTERIOR BOXES WITH A CLASS 2 NON-FLAMMABLE GAS DIAMOND LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE BOXES. RESPONDER OPNED THE OTHER BOXES AND ALL HAD THE SAME TWO BOXES WITH DIAMOND LABELS ON THEM INSIDE. THEN CONTACTED THE HAZMAT SUPPORT DESK AND WAS INSTRUCTED TAKE PICTURES ON 6-SIDES, TO ISOLATE THE PACKAGES FOR INVESTIGATION, AND COMPLETE UNDECLARED HAZMAT FORMS IN ETT. PACKAGES ARE BEING KEPT IN HAZMAT AUDITING AREA. ADDITIONAL TRACKING NUMBERS: 1Z625A6W0337055830, 1Z625A6W0315604957, 1Z625A6W0310221665, 1Z625A6W0308167345, 1Z625A6W0303168906, 1Z625A6W0333328909, 1Z625A6W0308525725, 1Z625A6W0324364717, 1Z625A6W0318497676, 1Z625A6W0322117667, 1Z625A6W0325856809, 1Z625A6W0323824883, 1Z625A6W0315904883

column168: Driver reported to Origin Facility (generator). Once on-site made contact with provided site contact and was guided into the building. Hoses were connected to tanks designated by contact and material was pumped on into tanker. After completion of load and shipping documents, driver departed facility for Envirite of OH for offload. A long the route, driver stopped at gas station to use restroom and grab breakfast. When he was checking out, the attendant asked if he was in tanker and that is was leaking (a small hole had developed on the driver side rear of the tanker). Driver immediately went to the truck and deployed spill kit (additional grabbed material from gas station). Driver then made call to Emergency # listed on manifest. A resulting call back stated that a tanker/crew would be coming to assist with offload. County FD arrived on scene and driver provided them copy of manifest and ERG book. FD contacted Utility Commission to bring in dirt/sand to contain the area directly around the tank.  A call was made by operations to US Ecology (EQ) to see if they were mobilizing their tanker down to the site to assist (they did not receive any call). It was later determined that the ER # listed on the manifest was for the generator and they had no means to assist. Several emergency response vendors/Industrial vendors in the area were contacted and Hepaco ended up being the quickest to get on scene.
column169: The release is still currently under investigation.  Additional training program has already been implemented and on a more frequent basis (annually).  Also, additional training will be provided to all HazMat drivers on emergency spill procedures.

SequenceEvent: Upon inspection the box was unloaded with a damp exterior. Went to the van line to retrieve the package and once inspected I noticed the cap seal was not sealed completely which then contributed to the internal leak. The black protective bag kept majority of the liquid inside, estimated 1C. Absorbent pads was stuffed inside the bad to help contain the spill. DescribePack: The point of failure was no bottle itself, it was the protective seal underneath the cap. Wasn't completely sealed around the edges. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Gloves were worn to protect my skin. Absorbent pads were placed inside the bag to soak up the excess 1C liquid.

SequenceEvent: WHILE THE PACKAGE HANDLER WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER, THE PACKAGE WAS ON THE CONVEYOR BELT AND FELL OFF AND ONTO THE FLOOR.  THEY NOTICED THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING AND INFORMED THEIR MANAGER.  THE MANAGER QUICKLY INFORMED QA OF THE SITUATION.  QA GRABBED A RED TOTE LINED WITH A CLEAR, LARGE HAZMAT BAG AND FOLD ABSORB WITH NEUTRALIZER. THEY RUSHED OVER TO THE UNLOAD TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION.  THEY NOTICED THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS CORROSIVE AND WAS SITTING ON TOP OF THE GRATES.  THEY PLACED NEUTRALIZER ON THE AREA AND PLACED THE PACKAGE IN THE RED TOTE.  ONCE THE AREA WAS SAFE, THEY BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO QA AND PLACED IN THE HAZMAT PROCESSING CAGE. DescribePack: THE CONTAINER IS CRACKED ON THE BOTTOM CORNER FROM THE PACKAGE FALLING OFF THE BELT. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A RED HAZMAT TOTE LINED WITH A HAZMAT BAG AND NEUTRALIZER WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: customer came in to ship 4000lbs of equipment with multiple cases containing lithium batteries packed with equipment.   we have had issues with this shipper all summer not knowing the correct packaging and shipping labels for lithium batteries.  when they dropped this shipment off they said that all the cases were labeled correctly - I went back to the warehouse to look and noticed there were multiple cases that had damaged or torn DG Lit battery labels.  I advised the shipper they needed to have labels that were not torn or damaged. I actually took her back to the warehouse so she could see that they were not labeled correctly.  Her and her helper then sorted through the 100 plus cases to put the correct DG lit battery labels on them.  as we were getting a weight on them I asked her multiple times if they were ready to be accepted.  She said yes.  we palletized the shipment so we could get an actual weight on it to process the rest of the awb.  I advised her that we would be searching the shipment due to the nature of goods and that we were short staffed and would get to it as soon as possible.  We have had multiple problems with this customer shipping with us out of Nome, they repeatedly tell us that they "shipped it here like this" -   we found 17 cases that had issues.    7 cases have Lithium batteries, no label, terminals not protected,   1 case has 25lbs of lithium batteries.  1 case has 5 laptops no label  1 case has 2 cell phones no label   2 cases with power banks - 22lbs  multiple cases with spare lithium batteries but not enough equipment and terminals not protected. and 2 batteries appear to be damaged.  Nickel batteries with old DG/torn Dg labels on them  6 cases have lithium batteries no equipment,  also found contraband/marijuana - troopers were notified and they confiscated it.  loose 9v batteries,    One case contained over 150 lithium batteries, the majority thrown together into plastic bags with no protection on terminals.
column169: Better training for our vendor stations -  we heard multiple times from this shipper that they were able to ship their stuff here without any problems.  I hope that this shipment did not travel to OME like this but I think it might have.

column168: SNEU 144882 was discovered leaking clear liquid from a vapor line cap at the end of the tank. The Tank Closure on top of the tank was closed. Upon inspection it was found that a line valve was slightly open and product was present in the line. The vapor line cap gasket was cracked and leaking. The gasket was replaced, the valve closed and the liquid drained out of the line.
column169: During post-loading inspection, ensure that all closures are secured in the closed position, all blow-down lines are clear and all closure cap gaskets are intact and sealing. This should ensure that future incidents like this can be avoided.  Review the intermodal tank inspection and securement procedures and re-train the loading/unloading personnel.(NAR:389)

column168: A spill cleanup specialist located at our Memphis hub facility was called to the scene of a spill.  Package was found on the belt during the PM sort during normal sort procedures.  Inspection of the package found 2, 5L metal cans containing UN1263. There was no positive closure on the cans, no moisture barriers used, and no dunnage reported.  It was found one of the cans was leaking and allowed for an estimated .25L to escape.  Package was placed in a steel salvage drum and shipper was contacted for an amended shipper's declaration for continued travel.

At 1228 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics (LEP) about a cargo release. It was reported that due to unknown reasons, approximately 5 gallons of Blue Whale Muriatic Acid (Hazardous - UN1789) was released. The caller stated that the released product was contained to the trailer floor at dock door #43. ERTS dispatched GrayMar to conduct cleanup operations. At 1500 ET GrayMar personnel arrived onsite and reports that almost all of the boxes are wet from leaking caps on the one gallon poly jugs. The entire pallet of boxed jugs was broken down and containerized. Two 55 gallon and two 20 gallon poly drums were generated containing the jugs only. One 55 gallon poly drum containing the impacted cardboard, debris, and absorbent pads was also generated. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On September 2, 2022, at 1616 ET, Coca-Cola Consolidated reported 170-gallons of UN1824 "Advantis 330" released from a tanker trailer impacting asphalt and a storm drain. HEPACO was dispatched to the site to perform clean-up activities. On September 2, 2022, at 1800 ET, HEPACO personnel arrived on site and estimated 150-gallons of product was released and impacted an area 10-feet (ft.) by 15-ft. of concrete drive/loading dock and a storm drain. HEPACO applied a citric acid neutralizer, pad and granular absorbents to absorb and solidify the impacted areas, collected, containerized in a 55-gallon poly drum, and transported the waste offsite for disposal. HEPACO utilized a vacuum truck to recover the released material from the storm drain catch basin followed by a hot water flushing of the drain to recover residual impacts. Approximately 200-gallons of liquids were recovered and transported offsite for disposal.

THERE WAS ALSO A PUMP SPRAY SANITIZING SPRAY, IT DID NOT SAY FLAMMABLE OR HAVE ANY GHS LABELS, AND SOME ALCOHOL WIPES WHICH MIGHT BE ELIGILBLE FOR IATA SPECIAL PROVISION A46 AS NONHAZ IF THE CRITERIA FOR A46 IS MET. column169: Joint RCFA investigation between VSP Technologies and Groendyke Transport found hardware failure and possible previous process failures causing a loss of clamping force to the gasketed flange connection.    Preventative Measures taken: 1) All flange/sump connection flanges need to have the "Class Rating" of the hardware verified, or changed out to confirm proper hardware. 2) Working on a kit program whereas all hardware, gaskets, etc. for a proper joint connection are supplied together as a kit. 3) Training of personnel by the manufacturer as to the proper equipment, installation, and torque processes in order to ensure a leak-free connection. This process has already been started.

column168: While a Buffalo Southern RR (BSOR) conductor was preparing a string of cars to be moved at BC Yard in Buffalo, he observed that a hissing sound coming from the manway atop tank car CGTX 65310. He notified the remaining crew to remain in the locomotive and await further instruction. This was at approximately 15: 15 hrs. The conductor notified a senior BSOR employee of the situation and a call was place at approximately 15:22 to Patrick Connors, CMO and train operation manager. A call was also placed to Steve Meyers, FRA for guidance. It was decided to have the conductor call the Chemtrec emergency response center. (Chemtrec Report #2022090706314) Patrick Connors began making calls to BSOR management and the shipper to begin a response plan, as well as the NRC and NYSDOT. Delays in making direct contact to the shipper resulted in a decision being made to contact a contractor to respond immediately to the location. A call was placed to the Norfolk Southern Yardmaster and MTO to alert them of the situation and its location. Train operations were halted on the adjoining track. The contractor arrived at the location at approximately 17:20. The contractor metered the air quality and inspected the car. They opened the protective housing lid and found the 8-side liquid line frozen with a visible vapor leak of propane. they also observed the secondary plug on the liquid line was not tool-tight, with peeling thread tape. They tightened the plug, but noticed the leak did not cease even after being tool-tight. They then relieved plug pressure by purging frozen materials, and resealed the valve. and at 18:30 noted the leak had ceased. At 1845 hrs, the wiped down the plug and valve threads, applied new thread tape to the secondary plug and used a Multi-Rae multi meter and soapy water solution to verify that the valve was closed. Pat Connors of the BSOR called all the contacted parties to advise them of the containment of the release. The NS was contacted to allow for the resumption of their train operations.
column169: Procedures or training to shippers who load tank cars to be sure all valves and fittings that require tool-tightening have indeed been tool tightened.

column168: An undeclared hazardous material was discovered following a completed waste shipment. The undeclared material was 18.3 grams of U-238 (depleted uranium). A Hazardous Waste Shipment left the Framatome site on August 5, 2022 for Clean Earth Specialty Waste Solutions in Tacoma Washington. On September 22, 2022 at about 11 :30, a Framatome Waste Engineer informed Framatome EHS&L (Environmental Health Safety and Licensing) management that this shipment included waste that had not passed the free release criteria for radioactive waste. The shipment included seven containers that went to Clean Earth Specialty Waste Solutions in Tacoma, Washington on the August 5th, 2022 shipment. To date, five of the seven waste containers have been returned to Framatome and have been confirmed that no radioactive material was present. The first of the two remaining waste packages is listed in sections 14, 26 and 27 above. The second package included material not regulated by DOT, (WA state dangerous waste only, Toxic). Both packages were of the same UN specification markings.
column169: Operating procedures are being updated and personnel will be trained to those procedure changes to help prevent recurrence. Recommendation: The return of our waste shipment required (b.y regulation) the same proper shipping name as originally listed. The presence of radioactive material changed the labels and steps required for the return shipment. Suggest allowing changes to the proper shipping name for previously undeclared hazardous material.

column168: Driver shut down the pump operations while loading to wait for maintenance to arrive at the location and repair the truck. While waiting, the truck's power was turned off rendering the Coriolis meter powerless. Because the two truck compartments did not have power, both compartments were open which caused the oil to equalize in the two compartments. After the truck was repaired, the driver restarted the loading process. The driver did not realize that there was already 36 bbls. of oil in the rear compartment. After loading, the total was 6 bbl. short of an overfill, but because it was so close to the maximum fill, there was a surge resulting in 5 gallons leaking out of the trailer vent line onto the ground.
column169: Discussed with the driver the errors and assumptions that lead to the event and retrained driver in loading procedures

column168: Environmental Options, Inc (EOI) truck was en route to Environmental Enterprises Inc (EEI) in Marion VA with a load of hazardous waste. The tractor became disabled on the shoulder of I-81 at MM 59.5 EOI first contacted EEI who dispatched a tractor to the site to pull the trailer to EEI located in Marion VA. When EEI arrived they discovered something was leaking out of the nose of the trailer and thought a chlorine vapor was observed when checking the load. EEI contacted Leann Herman with Environmental Options of the situation. Ms. Herman then contacted the State Police , First Call Environmental to respond to a hazmat incident. The response time was going to be at least 3 hours. Ms.Herman then reached out to Elizabeth Lohman with the Office of Pollution Response & Emergency Preparedness (Department of Environmental Quality VA). Due to other hazmat on board and the wait time for First Call to be on scene, Scott Sproles the Regional HazMat officer with VDEM was dispatched to the scene of the incident and called in Wythe County Emergency Services to help. During this time the NRC, VEOC were also notified. DEQ contacted Virginia Department of Transportation (VDOT) to dispatch the Safety Patrol Operator to evaluate need for traffic control and a lane closure was put into place. The initial incident report to the NRC indicated it could be chlorine tabs gasing off (Incident Report# 1346219). Once the hazmat crew was on scene and load was transferred to another trailer. A leaking drum of nitric acid was discovered. Ms Herman updated her NRC incident report under (Incident Report # 1346275) to show 10 gallons of nitric acid/nickel solution was released. The leaking poly drum was placed into an overpack and the spilled material was neutralized and collected for proper disposal. A follow up call the NRC was made on 09/03 to update the clean up procedure (Incident report # 1346306).
